15.3 General Social Survey

15.3.1 Exercises

  1. Explore the distribution of rincome (reported income). What makes the default bar chart hard to understand? How could you improve the plot?
gss_cat %>%
  ggplot(aes(rincome)) +
    geom_bar()

The default x-axis labels arent easily readable because of the long category names Rotating the text 90 degrees should work - alternatively, the ggstance has horizontal plot options that might be worth a try.

gss_cat %>%
  ggplot(aes(rincome)) +
    geom_bar() +
    theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle=90))

  1. What is the most common relig in this survey? Whats the most common partyid?
gss_cat %>%
  ggplot(aes(relig)) +
    geom_bar() +
    theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle=90))

gss_cat %>%
  ggplot(aes(partyid)) +
    geom_bar() +
    theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle=90))

The most common religion is Protestant. The most common single response for party ID is Independent, but if groupings were combined based on strong + not-strong party affilitation things would look a bit different.

  1. Which relig does denom (denomination) apply to? How can you find out with a table? How can you find out with a visualisation?
gss_cat %>%
  group_by(relig) %>%
  count(denom) %>%
  arrange(desc(n))

Denomination is primarily applicable for Protestant religious respondents.

gss_cat %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = relig, y = denom)) +
    geom_count() +
    theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle=90))

15.4 Modifying factor order

15.4.1 Exercises

  1. There are some suspiciously high numbers in tvhours. Is the mean a good summary?
gss_cat %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = relig, y = tvhours)) +
    geom_boxplot()

The distribution appears to be quite skewed across most religions, so lets look at using the median as a measure of central tendency instead.

relig <- gss_cat %>%
  group_by(relig) %>%
  summarise(
    age = mean(age, na.rm = TRUE),
    tvhours = median(tvhours, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n()
  )
ggplot(relig, aes(tvhours, fct_reorder(relig, tvhours))) +
  geom_point()

  1. Why did moving Not applicable to the front of the levels move it to the bottom of the plot?

Because in that case the factor is on the y-axis and y-axis values are plotted going upward from the bottom.

15.5 Modifying factor levels

15.5.1 Exercises

  1. How have the proportions of people identifying as Democrat, Republican, and Independent changed over time?
gss_cat %>%
  mutate(partyid = fct_collapse(partyid,
    other = c("No answer", "Don't know", "Other party"),
    rep = c("Strong republican", "Not str republican"),
    ind = c("Ind,near rep", "Independent", "Ind,near dem"),
    dem = c("Not str democrat", "Strong democrat")
  )) %>%
  group_by(year, partyid) %>%
  count() %>%
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = prop, colour = partyid)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_point()

  1. How could you collapse rincome into a small set of categories?
levels(gss_cat$rincome)
 [1] "No answer"      "Don't know"     "Refused"       
 [4] "$25000 or more" "$20000 - 24999" "$15000 - 19999"
 [7] "$10000 - 14999" "$8000 to 9999"  "$7000 to 7999" 
[10] "$6000 to 6999"  "$5000 to 5999"  "$4000 to 4999" 
[13] "$3000 to 3999"  "$1000 to 2999"  "Lt $1000"      
[16] "Not applicable"
gss_cat %>%
  mutate(rincome = fct_collapse(
    rincome,
    "Unknown" = c("No answer", "Don't know", "Refused"),
    "Lt $10000" = c("$8000 to 9999", "$7000 to 7999", "$6000 to 6999", "$5000 to 5999", "$4000 to 4999", "$3000 to 3999", "$1000 to 2999", "Lt $1000"),
    "$10000 to 19999" = c("$15000 - 19999", "$10000 - 14999"),
    "$20000 or more" = c("$25000 or more", "$20000 - 24999")
  )) %>%
  count(rincome)
